# What impact have the power outages had on the everyday lives of Ukrainian citizens?

## Summary
The Russian army has been targeting Ukraine's energy infrastructure for the past month, resulting in 40% of facilities destroyed and power cuts in many cities <font color=#FF3399>[1]</font>. This has had a serious impact on everyday life for Ukrainians, with rolling power cuts introduced to save energy and longer wait times for the Kyiv subway <font color=#FF3399>[2,3]</font>. Civilians are getting increasingly fearful of the dark and cold winter ahead <font color=#FF3399>[3]</font>. Houses are often without power or internet, so communication is difficult <font color=#FF3399>[4]</font>. To cope, some are trying to stay positive and continue with their activities, such as dancing <font color=#FF3399>[5]</font>.

## Claims
| Claim Sentence | Context |
|---|---|
|<font color=#FF3399>[1]</font> The lack of electricity has resulted in power cuts in many cities, especially Kyiv, affecting thousands of homes.<a href="https://www.dw.com/en/war-in-ukraine-kyiv-prepares-for-a-blackout/a-63716304" target="_blank">Source</a>| For the past month, the Russian army has increasingly been targeting Ukraine's energy infrastructure. Around 40% of facilities have already been destroyed, according to Ukrainian authorities. The lack of electricity has resulted in power cuts in many cities, especially Kyiv, affecting thousands of homes. Oleksandr Dyachenko, also from Kyiv, is well prepared.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[2]</font> Many Ukrainians are without electricity or water supplies.<a href="https://www.dw.com/en/ukraine-power-outages-become-a-daily-reality/video-63619441" target="_blank">Source</a>| 11/01/2022 November 1, 2022 Russian airstrikes have seriously damaged more than a third of Ukraine's energy infrastructure. Many Ukrainians are without electricity or water supplies. Rolling power cuts were introduced to save energy while engineers carry out repairs.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[3]</font> Civilians in Ukraine are "getting more and more fearful" as Moscow escalates attacks on critical infrastructure, leaving many residents without power.<a href="https://www.cnn.com/europe/live-news/russia-ukraine-war-news-11-04-22/h_d23a02d484052163a223381ea3b507a4" target="_blank">Source</a>| Civilians in Ukraine are "getting more and more fearful" as Moscow escalates attacks on critical infrastructure, leaving many residents without power. "We are seeing people actually getting more and more fearful about what an increasingly dark and cold winter might mean," CNN's Christiane Amanpour told Don Lemon on "CNN This Morning" from Kyiv.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[4]</font> Every time the power shuts off, the family loses internet service.<a href="https://apnews.com/article/russia-ukraine-kyiv-europe-power-outages-59e75904f889cb6039827daf73bf4c0d" target="_blank">Source</a>| Starting Tuesday, the government plans to change the schedule of the Kyiv subway to include longer wait times to save energy. On the day that The Associated Press visited Vedmids house in October, there was an unscheduled five-hour power outage and then a scheduled one during dinner. Every time the power shuts off, the family loses internet service. Because the village also has a weak phone network, the household is often unable to communicate with others.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[5]</font> "I'm not going to stop dancing, because it really saves us."<a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-63539470" target="_blank">Source</a>| "Of course, it's stressful for people, but we try to find a way out in a positive way," says Yana. "I'm not going to stop dancing, because it really saves us."|
